2:30.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927846/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927846/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927846/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-06-20","Compass Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 12 March 2018 to Question HL5946 on asylum: housing, if he will publish the criteria set out in the COMPASS contracts on the allocation of shared rooms; and whether the Government has made an assessment of the level of compliance with that criteria.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","155929"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927847","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-06-29","<p>In supporting victims of domestic violence, DWP offers a range of support open to survivors and those still experiencing domestic abuse.</p><p>Jobcentre staff delivering Universal Credit undergo a comprehensive learning journey designed to equip them with the tools, skills and behaviours required to provide a high quality service to all claimants. Specific training and guidance is provided for working with different vulnerable groups, including people who have been the victims of domestic violence.</p><p>This can include signposting claimants to national and local organisations that provide specialist support. Work coaches can also apply a domestic violence easement, switching off a claimant’s all work-related requirements for a period of time.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-06-29T10:08:16.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927847/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927847/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927847/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-06-20","Universal Credit: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether training on domestic abuse will be provided for people working on the application and administration of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","155866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927848","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-06-29","<p>The policy to provide additional Universal Credit support for a maximum of two children encourages families who receive benefits to make the same financial decisions as those families who support themselves solely through work.</p><p> </p><p>Exceptions are an important part of the policy and we have always been clear they will be delivered in the most effective, compassionate way, with the right safeguards in place.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to monitor the impact of the policy. <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2018-04-27/HCWS653/" target="_blank">Written Statement HCWS653</a> on 27 April outlined a recent change to the policy</p><p> </p><p>It is worth noting that Child Benefit continues to be paid for all children plus an additional amount for any disabled children. Additional help for eligible childcare costs are also available regardless of the total number of children in the household.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-06-29T12:18:09.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927848/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927848/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927848/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-06-20","Social Security Benefits: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether her Department plans to review the two-child benefit cap.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","155867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927849","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-06-28","<p>The law is absolutely clear that pregnancy and maternity discrimination in the workplace is unlawful. Government is tackling pregnancy and maternity discrimination in several ways.</p><p> </p><p>Firstly, Government is working to increase awareness of individuals’ rights and employers’ obligations. We have made steady progress.</p><p> </p><p>- ACAS published updated guidance in November, so that women and employers understand their rights and obligations better. Government also continues to support the Equality &amp; Human Rights Commission’s Working Forward campaign on pregnancy and maternity discrimination.</p><p> </p><p>- The MAT B1 form (the form which enables a pregnant woman to claim Statutory Maternity Pay from her employer or Maternity Allowance from Jobcentre Plus) has recently been updated to include a link to advice and guidance on employment rights for pregnant women and new mothers.</p><p> </p><p>- The Government’s response to the Taylor Review of modern working practices committed to update and consolidate the pregnancy and maternity discrimination pages on GOV.UK by summer 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Secondly, the Government has committed to review the legislation relating to redundancy protection and consider whether this is sufficient. This review is underway.</p><p> </p><p>Thirdly, in terms of monitoring and enforcement, Government continues to fund both the ACAS helpline and the Equality Advisory and Support Service, which provide free advice in this area. Government will also monitor others’ findings (such as the recent EHRC work poll on employer attitudes) for any signs that interventions are starting to have an impact or changes in employers’ practices.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-06-28T11:29:27.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927849/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927849/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927849/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-06-20","Pregnancy: Discrimination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps the Government is taking to tackle maternity discrimination.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","155868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927850","Women and Equalities","false","2018-06-25","<p>The Government is committed to supporting victims of revenge porn, and funds the Revenge Porn Helpline, which has received over 10,000 calls since it opened in February 2015.</p><p>The Government has awarded £80,000 to the Helpline for the 2018/19 financial year, to ensure victims of revenge porn continue to receive the support they need.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-06-25T13:50:32.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927850/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927850/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927850/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2018-06-20","Pornography: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what steps the Government is taking to protect women and men who experience revenge porn.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","155869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927851","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-25","<p>The Secretary of State for Transport and the Roads Minister discuss issues affecting Highways England regularly with the Chief Executive of Highways England, and these discussions are continued at official level. Issues covered include the provision of litter collection by the side of the Strategic Road Network and progress on delivery of commitments set out in the Government Litter Strategy 2017.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-06-25T12:52:13.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927851/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927851/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927851/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-20","Roads: Litter","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with Highways England on the removal of litter from the edge of the roads for which that organisation has responsibility.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","155718"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927852","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-25","<p>The Driver &amp; Vehicle Standards Agency has published guidance on securing loads carried on vehicles. The guidance states that tarpaulins or netting/sheeting should be used on tippers, bulk containers and skips to stop loose items from falling.</p><p> </p><p>The Litter Strategy for England 2017 sets out the commitment of the Government and Highways England to a range of measures to reduce roadside litter on motorways and a small number of all-purpose trunk roads. The responsibility for litter clearance on the rest of the trunk road network lies with the relevant local district and borough councils.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-06-25T11:46:48.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927852/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927852/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927852/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-20","Roads: Litter","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with the (a)  Freight Transport Association and (b) Road Haulage Association on measures to prevent litter from being blown off open lorries and left as litter on the roadside.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","155719"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927853","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-26","<p>The Litter Strategy for England contains commitments to work with Highways England and others to tackle litter on the roadside, and to work with local councils, ports and the haulage industry to improve facilities for hauliers, fishing vessels and others to dispose of their litter and waste.</p><p>Defra Ministers have met their Department for Transport counterparts to discuss these issues and agree measures to reduce and remove litter from the Strategic Road Network. Highways England was also represented at these meetings.</p><p>Defra Ministers also raised the issue of litter at a meeting with the Road Haulage Association and the Freight Transport Association in January this year, and the Department has written to both organisations following the introduction of new local authority powers to tackle littering from vehicles in April this year.</p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley",,"2018-06-26T10:02:08.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927853/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927853/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927853/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-06-20","Roads: Litter","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions he has had with (a) the Secretary of State for Transport, (b) Highways England, (c) the Road Haulage Association and (d) the Freight Transport Association on preventing and removing roadside litter.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","155720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927854","Treasury","false","2018-06-28","<p>The data to answer questions 155901 and 155902 is not readily available and could only be provided at a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The rollout of Tax-Free Childcare began in April 2017 to a small number of parents. Only a limited number of accounts have been open more than one year so accurate and robust data on the annual value of top-up paid to parents will not be available until early 2019, one year after full rollout of TFC.</p><p> </p><p>For question 155904 I refer the honourable member to the answer I gave on 4 December 2017 to the honourable member for Batley and Spen (116593).</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","155902 ; 155903 ; 155904","2018-06-28T11:45:50.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927854/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927854/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927854/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-06-20","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the average payment is from tax-free childcare accounts to families where parents are higher rate tax payers since those accounts were established.","false","Biography information for Emma Little Pengelly","Belfast South","Emma Little Pengelly","155901"
