"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927973","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-06-25","<p>There are no plans to publish this analysis.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-06-25T15:25:21.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927973/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927973/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927973/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-06-20","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Treasury's response to the Treasury Committee's Ninth Report of Session 2017-19 on Childcare, if she will publish the internal analysis on families reaching the Universal Credit childcare costs support cap.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","155896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927974","Treasury","false","2018-06-28","<p>The Serious Fraud Office began an investigation into the manipulation of interbank lending rates in 2012.</p><p> </p><p>In relation to EURIBOR, 11 individuals have been charged, five of whom are currently at trial. One defendant has pleaded guilty to the charges. There are currently European Arrest Warrants issued in respect of the remaining five suspects.</p><p> </p><p>In relation to LIBOR, 13 individuals have had criminal proceedings brought against them. Four trials have concluded, which includes a retrial. These trials have resulted in five convictions and eight acquittals.</p><p> </p><p>No organisation has been charged as part of the SFO investigations, but the FCA have fined seven banks a total of over £757m for LIBOR and EURIBOR related misconduct. There have also been enforcement proceedings in other jurisdictions.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","155657","2018-06-28T15:21:45.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927974/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927974/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927974/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-06-20","LIBOR: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) individuals and (b) organisations have been charged with rigging LIBOR since 2010; and what the outcome was of those charges.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","155656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927975","Treasury","false","2018-06-28","<p>The Serious Fraud Office began an investigation into the manipulation of interbank lending rates in 2012.</p><p> </p><p>In relation to EURIBOR, 11 individuals have been charged, five of whom are currently at trial. One defendant has pleaded guilty to the charges. There are currently European Arrest Warrants issued in respect of the remaining five suspects.</p><p> </p><p>In relation to LIBOR, 13 individuals have had criminal proceedings brought against them. Four trials have concluded, which includes a retrial. These trials have resulted in five convictions and eight acquittals.</p><p> </p><p>No organisation has been charged as part of the SFO investigations, but the FCA have fined seven banks a total of over £757m for LIBOR and EURIBOR related misconduct. There have also been enforcement proceedings in other jurisdictions.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","155656","2018-06-28T15:21:45.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927975/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927975/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927975/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-06-20","EURIBOR: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) individuals and (b) organisations have been charged with rigging EURIBOR since 2010; and what the outcome was of those charges.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","155657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927976","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-29","<p>Network Rail have closed the Severn Tunnel in preparation for electrification from London to Cardiff from 16<sup>th</sup> June – 7<sup>th</sup> July.</p><p> </p><p>In preparation for the £5 billion modernisation of the Great Western Mainline, the Department funded the Swindon to Kemble redoubling project to provide a robust diversionary route for passengers and freight to South Wales.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-06-29T10:32:55.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927976/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927976/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927976/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-20","Severn Tunnel: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the economic effect of the temporary closure of the Severn Tunnel.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","155762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927977","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-29","<p>The overhead conductor system is showing early signs of deterioration because of the wet and corrosive environment in the Severn Tunnel.</p><p> </p><p>Network Rail have identified this early on and are addressing this matter prior to energisation of the electrification system.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-06-29T10:36:57.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927977/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927977/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927977/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-20","Severn Tunnel: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether electrical equipment installed during the previous closure of the Severn Tunnel has rusted.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","155763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927978","Department for Education","false","2018-06-25","<p>As at 31 May 2018, there were 26 full time equivalent members of staff working on the 30 hours free childcare policy out of 81.2 full time equivalent staff working in the Department for Education’s Early Years Group. Other staff members in the department also contribute to early years policy, including the 30 hours free childcare policy, as part of their work.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-06-25T14:50:24.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927978/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927978/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927978/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-06-20","Department for Education: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 14 June 2018 to Question 152263 on Department for Education: Staff, what proportion of the 81.2 equivalent full time staff work on the 30 hours of funded childcare policy.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","155897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927979","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-06-25","<p>The UK £25m contribution to the Commonwealth Marine Plastics Research and Innovation Framework will come from a number of Official Development Assistance (ODA) and non-ODA sources, including planned government-funded research and innovation activities and new activities from unallocated budgets.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-06-25T14:00:39.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927979/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927979/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927979/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-06-20","Plastics: Marine Environment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the Marine Plastics Research and Innovation Framework will have funding allocated from Official Development Aid.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","155717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927980","Department for Education","false","2018-06-27","<p>We know that having poor speech, language and communication skills can hold children back at school and limit their life chances thereafter. This was identified as an issue in all 12 of the Opportunity Areas. We are putting plans in place to address this.</p><p> </p><p>For example:</p><p> </p><ul><li>In Stoke-on-Trent we are building on the successful “Stoke Speaks Out” initiative, extending this to 25 primary schools with lower than average numbers of children attaining a Good Level of Development by the end of their reception year. This is a proven approach to providing targeted, specialist support for early language, communication and literacy;</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>In Oldham, we have committed to ensuring that all children are school ready by the age of five, and have already completed training 29 schools and settings in our Making it REAL programme, which focusses on early literacy and development. 254 children have already been supported; and</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>In the North Yorkshire Coast OA, we have commissioned work to develop improved speech, language and communication support for children in the early years. 25 primary schools will participate in this.</li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p><br>We are working to ensure that the learning from these initiatives will be shared across other areas of the country facing challenges.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-06-27T13:54:04.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927980/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927980/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927980/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-06-20","Children: Communication Skills","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans he has to support opportunity areas in the development of plans to improve speech, language and communications skills among children and young people.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","155764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927981","Attorney General","false","2018-07-03","<p>The SFO has brought charges against four employees including former chief executives of Barclays Plc as part of its criminal investigation into Barclays and its capital raising arrangements with Qatar Holding LLC and Challenger Universal Ltd in June and October 2008. The case is ongoing.</p><p>Additionally, a total of 13 employees including former senior bankers have so far had criminal proceedings commenced against them for fraudulently fixing the London Interbank Offered Rate (LIBOR) in the run up to and during the crisis - four trials have concluded including a retrial. So far, in total, there have been five convictions and eight acquittals. Those convicted were jailed for a total of more than 27 years and each received confiscation orders totalling hundreds of thousands of pounds.</p><p>The SFO has also charged 11 employees including former senior bankers in respect of fixing the European Interbank Offered Rate (EURIBOR), five of which are currently at trial. One defendant, Christian Bittar, a former Managing Director, has pleaded guilty to the charges. There are currently European Arrest Warrants issued in respect of the remaining five suspects.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2018-07-03T14:32:29.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927981/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927981/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927981/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2018-06-20","Financial Services: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many (a) bank employees and (b) directors have been prosecuted for their role in the 2007-08 financial crisis; and what the outcome was of those prosecutions.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","155658"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927982","Department for Education","false","2018-06-27","<p>The Early Years Workforce Strategy, published in March 2017, included a commitment that the department would develop criteria for the content of level 2 early years practitioner qualifications.</p><p> </p><p>An expert reference group provided advice, guidance and challenge. Membership of the group included academics, technical, employer and training provider expertise.</p><p> </p><p>In December 2017, we published a 12-week online consultation seeking views on the proposed criteria. We are now revising the criteria based on the consultation feedback and will publish them with a government response by September. The criteria will require qualifications to include skills and knowledge to support early language development and children with additional needs.</p><p> </p><p>The Early Years Workforce Strategy is at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/early-years-workforce-strategy" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/early-years-workforce-strategy</a>. <br> <br> The level 2 qualification consultation documents are at: <a href="https://consult.education.gov.uk/childcare-providers-and-regulation/improving-level-2-qualifications-for-the-early-edu/" target="_blank">https://consult.education.gov.uk/childcare-providers-and-regulation/improving-level-2-qualifications-for-the-early-edu/</a>.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-06-27T13:49:44.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927982/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927982/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927982/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-06-20","Special Educational Needs: Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans he has to ensure that the identification of speech, language and communication problems are a core requirement of Level 2 qualifications for early years teachers.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","155765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927983","Treasury","false","2018-06-28","<p>The details of enforcement actions taken by the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) and Prudential Regulation Authority (PRA), including fines levied on banks, are published on their websites.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-06-28T15:17:43.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927983/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927983/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927983/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-06-20","Bank Services: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish the (a) fines and (b) penalties levied on banks authorised to operate in the UK since 2010.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","155659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927984","Treasury","false","2018-06-28","<p>This is a matter for the operationally independent Financial Conduct Authority (FCA).</p><p> </p><p>This report was provided to the FCA and the police at the time, in 2014.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA is currently investigating the extent and nature of the knowledge of the discovery of misconduct within HBOS Impaired Assets office in Reading and HBOS’ communications with the regulator after the initial discovery of the misconduct.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","155661 ; 155662","2018-06-28T15:27:19.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927984/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927984/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927984/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-06-20","Halifax Bank of Scotland: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans to publish the full Turnbull report on alleged frauds at HBOS.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","155660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927985","Treasury","false","2018-06-28","<p>This is a matter for the operationally independent Financial Conduct Authority (FCA).</p><p> </p><p>This report was provided to the FCA and the police at the time, in 2014.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA is currently investigating the extent and nature of the knowledge of the discovery of misconduct within HBOS Impaired Assets office in Reading and HBOS’ communications with the regulator after the initial discovery of the misconduct.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","155660 ; 155662","2018-06-28T15:27:19.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927985/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927985/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927985/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-06-20","Halifax Bank of Scotland: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when (a) he and (b) officials in his Department were made aware of the draft Turnbull Report on alleged frauds at HBOS.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","155661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927986","Treasury","false","2018-06-28","<p>This is a matter for the operationally independent Financial Conduct Authority (FCA).</p><p> </p><p>This report was provided to the FCA and the police at the time, in 2014.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA is currently investigating the extent and nature of the knowledge of the discovery of misconduct within HBOS Impaired Assets office in Reading and HBOS’ communications with the regulator after the initial discovery of the misconduct.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","155660 ; 155661","2018-06-28T15:27:20.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927986/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927986/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927986/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-06-20","Halifax Bank of Scotland: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with regulatory bodies on the contents of the Turnbull Report on alleged frauds at HBOS .","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","155662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927987","Treasury","false","2018-06-29","<p>HMRC is looking very closely at the information the ICIJ has released in the Paradise Papers to see if it reveals anything new that could add to their existing leads and investigations.</p><p> </p><p>In a significant number of cases that HMRC have reviewed, the practices and schemes which the data points to were either already known to HMRC or have no UK tax consequences. Since 2010, HMRC has brought in more that £2.8 billion from domestic and global initiatives to tackle offshore tax evaders.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-06-29T09:39:46.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927987/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927987/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927987/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-06-20","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress his Department has made on its inquiry into the Paradise Papers.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","155663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927988","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-27","<p>As of 1 June 2018, there are 26,792,900 people who hold valid United Kingdom European Health Insurance Cards.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-06-27T16:00:26.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927988/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927988/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927988/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-06-20","Health Services: Reciprocal Arrangements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many people held European Health Insurance cards as of 1 June 2018.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","155694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927989","Department for International Development","false","2018-06-28","<p>The Department for International Development has zero tolerance to any incidents of fraud and corruption and has developed robust systems to identify and mitigate those risks, at all levels. The department retains information on all suspected and confirmed cases of fraud and corruption and this information is regularly reviewed to identify anomalies and trends. This insight is shared internally on a regular basis and used to drive a risk-based and proactive approach to fraud across the portfolio.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-06-28T16:20:22.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927989/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927989/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927989/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-06-20","Overseas Aid: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent assessment she has made of trends in the level of fraud in the expenditure of Official Development Aid in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","155695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927990","Department for International Development","false","2018-06-28","<p>Following the 2016 Multilateral Development Review, it was found that EuropeAid has systems and policies in place to tackle fraud and corruption. Since its publication, DFID officials have met with the European Commission and OLAF to discuss best practice, with a focus on staff awareness of their responsibilities in identifying and raising fraud and corruption concerns.</p><p>DFID’s dedicated specialist Counter Fraud Section (CFS) is focused on stamping out fraud before it occurs. CFS work in partnership with a number of International agencies including OLAF (European Anti-fraud Office), through an established information sharing agreement. This is used to share intelligence on activities that could impact on overseas development assistance.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-06-28T16:19:16.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927990/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927990/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927990/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-06-20","EU Aid: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what representations her Department has made to the EU on fraud in relation to EU overseas development assistance in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","155696"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927991","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-06-28","<p>Government is continuing to assess the impact of leaving the EU on the voluntary, community and social enterprise (VCSE) sector, including around funding. The National Council for Voluntary Organisations estimate that in 2014/15 the UK voluntary sector received between £350-450 million of EU funding. Estimates for 2016 are not yet available.</p><p> </p><p>There are a wide range of EU funds that community and voluntary sector organisations access. Government is actively listening to the views of community and voluntary sector organisations as we develop successor funding schemes to EU programmes</p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-06-28T15:07:10.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927991/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927991/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927991/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-06-20","EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of public monies received by the (a) community and (b) voluntary sector came from the EU.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","155697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927992","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-28","<p>​We are aware of reports about the recent arrests of journalists, activists and human rights defenders in Egypt, and we have raised this with the Egyptian Government, most recently in May. The UK wishes to see more political progress and better protection of human rights in Egypt, which is why Egypt is an Foreign and Commonwealth Office Human Rights Priority Country. Our concerns about restrictions on freedom of expression in Egypt have been raised by the Foreign Secretary who emphasised the importance of a free and open society with Egypt's President Sisi during his visit to Cairo in February 2017. Ministers consistently raise our human rights concerns with Egyptian interlocutors. We also raise our concerns in public, including at the UN Human Rights Council; in September 2017 our statement noted our concern about media freedom in Egypt.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-06-28T14:04:59.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927992/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927992/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927992/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-06-20","Egypt: Freedom of Expression","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with the Egyptian government on allegations of abuse by Egyptian security forces against journalists in that country.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","155698"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927993","Department for Education","false","2018-06-26","<p>The number of payroll, non-payroll and full-time equivalent staff employed in back office functions (those functions that support the running of the department, such as Human Resources and Finance) is shown in the table attached.</p><p>These figures include the Standards and Testing Agency, Education and Skills Funding Agency and Teaching Regulation Agency who are Department for Education staff.</p><p>The School Teachers’ Review Body has no staff.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","155806 ; 155807 ; 155810 ; 155811","2018-06-26T12:51:10.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927993/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927993/answer","Staff_employed_within_back_office.doc","Number_of_back_office_staff_employed_by_department","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927993/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-06-20","Teaching Regulation Agency: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many (a) staff and (b) full-time equivalent staff work on (i) payroll and (ii) non-payroll back-office functions in the Teaching Regulation Agency.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","155802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927994","Women and Equalities","false","2018-06-25","<p>The Equality and Human Rights Commission is an independent public body and decisions on staffing requirements are operational matters for the Commission itself. I have therefore asked the Commission’s Chief Executive Officer to write to the Hon member with the information requested. I will place a copy of the letter in the libraries of both Houses.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-06-25T13:35:58.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927994/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927994/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927994/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2018-06-20","Equality and Human Rights Commission: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, how many (a) staff and (b) full-time equivalent staff are employed in (i) payroll and (ii) non-payroll back-office functions in the Equality and Human Rights Commission.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","155803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927995","Department for Education","false","2018-06-25","<p>This is a matter for LocatED. I have asked the Chief Executive, Lara Newman, to write to the hon. Member and a copy of her reply will be placed in the Libraries of both Houses.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-06-25T16:45:48.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927995/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927995/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927995/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-06-20","LocatED: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many (a) staff and (b) full-time equivalent staff are employed in (i) payroll and (ii) non-payroll back-office functions in LocatED.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","155804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927996","Department for Education","false","2018-06-25","<p>This is a matter for the Office of the Children’s Commissioner. I have asked the Children’s Commissioner, Anne Longfield, to write to the hon. Member and a copy of her reply will be placed in the Libraries of both Houses.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-06-25T16:44:02.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927996/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927996/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927996/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-06-20","Children's Commissioner for England: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many (a) staff and (b) full-time equivalent staff are employed in (i) payroll and (ii) non-payroll back-office functions in the Office of the Children’s Commissioner.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","155805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927997","Department for Education","false","2018-06-26","<p>The number of payroll, non-payroll and full-time equivalent staff employed in back office functions (those functions that support the running of the department, such as Human Resources and Finance) is shown in the table attached.</p><p>These figures include the Standards and Testing Agency, Education and Skills Funding Agency and Teaching Regulation Agency who are Department for Education staff.</p><p>The School Teachers’ Review Body has no staff.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","155802 ; 155807 ; 155810 ; 155811","2018-06-26T12:51:10.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927997/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927997/answer","Staff_employed_within_back_office.doc","Number_of_back_office_staff_employed_by_department","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927997/answer","Guildford","Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927997/answer/previousversion/65533","Biography information for Anne Milton","60","Education","Education","2018-06-20","School Teachers' Review Body: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many (a) staff and (b) full-time equivalent staff are employed in (i) payroll and (ii) non-payroll back-office functions in the School Teachers’ Review Body.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","155806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927998","Home Office","false","2018-06-25","<p>The Home Office does not publish support cessation data. Information on numbers of cases who have had support terminated broken down by reason for cessation and by area of the UK, is unavailable and could be produced only at a disproportionate cost.</p><p>Individuals whose claims for asylum have been refused and are appeal rights exhausted will lose access to s95 support unless they have children. S4 (2) support may be accessible if reasonable steps are being taken to leave the UK or there is a legal or practical obstacle that prevents departure.</p><p>Data on the number of asylum seekers in receipt of support is available:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2017/list-of-tables#asylum" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2017/list-of-tables#asylum</a> (Volume 4).</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-06-25T16:13:30.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927998/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927998/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927998/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-06-20","Asylum: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 11 May 2018 to Question 143752, on Asylum: Housing Benefit, for what reasons his Department does not publish data on the cessation of support.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","155777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927999","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-06-25","<p>We have interpreted “supported accommodation” as referring to Approved Premises, which provide residential accommodation in the community for female offenders who pose a medium risk of harm, as well as having complex resettlement needs.</p><p> </p><p>We are conducting a review into Approved Premises capacity for women, to ensure there is provision for women where it is needed. We are seeking to identify suitable provision for women in London and Wales, where we recognise that need is pressing.</p><p> </p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2018-06-25T14:19:57.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927999/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927999/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/927999/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-06-20","Offenders: Supported Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of (a) the availability and (b) the suitability of supported accommodation for female prisoners on release.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","155778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928000","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-06-25","<p>The change in the number of commissioned places in the three sectors of the under-18 estate is consistent with the sentencing practice of the courts and our policy of ensuring that young people are sent to custody only when there is no alternative. We will continue to ensure that enough places are available to ensure that the sentence of the court can be carried out.</p><p>The number of children entering the youth justice system has declined year on year, but many of those in our care demonstrate very challenging and complex behaviour.</p><p> </p><p>To deal with these challenges we are increasing frontline staff numbers in public-sector Young Offender Institutions and already have more than 200 officers enrolled on a specialist youth custody foundation degree.</p><p> </p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2018-06-25T14:29:57.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928000/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928000/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928000/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-06-20","Youth Custody","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the change in the number of commissioned beds in (a) secure children’s homes, (b) secure training centres and (c) young offender institutions since 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","155779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928001","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-06-25","<p>The total number of prisoners who have been transferred to hospital under sections 47 or 48 of the Mental Health Act 1983 in each of the last three years is set out below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2017</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>1,010</p></td><td><p>980</p></td><td><p>936</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The data are published annually on the gov.uk website under the Offender Management Statistics.</p><p> </p><p>The average time for such transfers to take place in each of those years has remained the same: 14 days.</p><p> </p><p>The time has been measured from the date at which the Ministry of Justice is provided with a complete application for a transfer warrant - indicating transfer is appropriate - to the actual date of admission to hospital. The Ministry of Justice has a target of 24 hours within which to provide a transfer warrant, once the assessments are complete and the two required medical reports and all other relevant information is received. This target is met in 95% of cases.</p><p> </p><p>This average time information is not published. The measure has been drawn from administrative IT systems which, as with any large-scale recording system, are subject to possible errors with data entry and processing.</p><p> </p><p>We take the mental health of prisoners extremely seriously, which is why we have increased the support available to vulnerable offenders - especially during the first 24 hours in custody - and invested more in mental health awareness training for prison officers.</p><p> </p><p>But we recognise that more can be done and continue to work in partnership with HMPPS, NHS England and Public Health England to improve mental health services for offenders at all points of the criminal justice system.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2018-06-25T14:25:31.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928001/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928001/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928001/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-06-20","Prisoners: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many transfers of prisoners to hospitals under the Mental Health Act 1983 there have been in each of the last three years; and what the average time was for such transfers to take place in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","155780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928002","Home Office","false","2018-06-28","<p>Pursuant to the reply to Question 137167 given to the hon. Member for Liverpool, Wavertree on 02 May, the Government is clear that where the Windrush generation have suffered loss, they will be compensated.</p><p>The first stage was to launch a Call for Evidence, that closed on 8 June. The Government will publish a further public consultation on the design and shape of the scheme, as soon as the time has been taken to analyse the responses to the Call for Evidence and use the information gathered to inform design and implementation considerations.</p><p>In the meanwhile we will continue to work with and support affected individuals through the operation of the Windrush Taskforce.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-06-28T13:56:21.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928002/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928002/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928002/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-06-20","Immigration: Windrush Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make an assessment she has made of the potential long-term trauma and detrimental effects on mental health caused to people affected by the Windrush scandal; and what steps the Government is taking to provide counselling, talking therapies and ongoing support to people affected and to their families.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","155781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928003","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-06-27","<p>The Government has no plans to amend the law on abortion in either England and Wales or Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p><p>Abortion has always been a devolved matter in Northern Ireland. The Government's priority is therefore restoring devolved government, so that the people of Northern Ireland, and locally elected representatives, can decide what is right for Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2018-06-27T14:40:22.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928003/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928003/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928003/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-06-20","Offences against the Person Act 1861: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, whether she will exercise her power under section 26(2) of the Northern Ireland Act 1998 to repeal sections 58 and 59 of the Offences Against the Person Act 1861 in order to comply with the UK's international obligations under the United Nations Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against Women.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","155724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928004","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-06-27","<p>Sector Deals are a new approach to the way Government works in partnership with industry to improve the productivity of their sector. Since the publication of the Industrial Strategy, four Deals have already been announced and there are more in discussion.</p><p> </p><p>Several sectors, including those in the clean energy sector, have expressed interest in a Sector Deal and we expect to progress with further Deals that best meet the expectations set out in the White Paper in due course.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-06-27T16:33:43.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928004/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928004/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928004/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-06-20","Energy: Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the timetable is for his Department to publish the Clean Energy Sector Deal.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","155725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928005","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-06-25","<p>The Department takes our responsibility for the prevention of error very seriously. We understand that the need to make sure payments are correct as incorrect payments will have implications for benefit claimants.</p><p>We ensure the accuracy and quality of payments through internal assurance processes. This enables the Department to identify and correct error and to focus on those points in the customer journey where there is a risk of error occurring.</p><p>When a benefit is reviewed the consequential impacts on other benefits are also reviewed.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","155813 ; 155814 ; 155835 ; 155836 ; 155838 ; 155840","2018-06-25T15:40:16.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928005/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928005/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/928005/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-06-20","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether her Department has identified errors in its calculation of personal independence payments in the last three months.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","155812"
